						               													<description>La Garde 6mm: Rules for Napoleonic grand tactical battles in 6mm.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The concept is to give &amp;quot;grand order&amp;quot;. That is to give orders to corps &amp;amp; divisional commanders, not to order a single battalion.&amp;#10;It is considered that a divisional or brigade commander ordered to take defensive positions will form his troops in square by himself if the need was to arise ...&amp;#10;&amp;#10;An original system with tokens is used to resolve combats. &amp;#10;Dice are used to determine reinforcements entry times and duration of the battle.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;The goal is to break the enemy morale, not just inflicting casualties.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Turn order sequence:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Preparation phases&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- Reinforcement phase&amp;#10;- Order phase&amp;#10;- Rally and officers replacement phase&amp;#10;- Initiative phase&amp;#10;- Army corps orders Disclosure&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Activation Cycle:&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- Activation phase&amp;#10;- Orders disclosure&amp;#10;- Movements and combats&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;     Consolidation Phase&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Game scale for ~6mm figures:&amp;#10;1cm = 20 meters.&amp;#10;3cm = 60 meters (width of the bases)&amp;#10;10cm = 200 meters (effective range of muskets)&amp;#10;60cm = 1200 meters (max range of 12 pounds of artillery pieces)&amp;#10;1m = 2km&amp;#10;A game turn last from 20 to 55 minutes.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;- User summary&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
